# TypeScript Patterns

## Error Handling with ts-result

Prefer `ts-result` for explicit error handling over try/catch:

```typescript
import { Ok, Err, Result } from 'ts-results'

// Return Result types for operations that can fail
function parseBookData(raw: unknown): Result<BookData, string> {
  if (!raw || typeof raw !== 'object') return Err('Invalid data format')

  const data = raw as Record<string, unknown>
  if (!data.title) return Err('Missing required field: title')

  const bookData = { title: String(data.title), ... }
  return Ok(bookData)
}

// Handle results with early returns
function processBook(raw: unknown) {
  const parseResult = parseBookData(raw)
  if (parseResult.err) return Err(`Failed to parse: ${parseResult.val}`)

  const book = parseResult.val
  // ... continue with valid data
  return Ok(book)
}
```

## When to Use ts-result vs Throwing

| Scenario                                            | Approach       |
| --------------------------------------------------- | -------------- |
| Expected failures (validation, parsing, API errors) | `Result<T, E>` |
| Programmer errors (invariant violations)            | `throw`        |
| Truly exceptional (out of memory, network down)     | `throw`        |
| Crossing module boundaries                          | `Result<T, E>` |

## Type Patterns

- Use `unknown` over `any` when type is truly unknown
- Prefer type inference where possible, explicit types at boundaries
- Use discriminated unions for state machines:

```typescript
type BookStatus = { status: 'pending' } | { status: 'complete'; completedAt: number } | { status: 'error'; errorMessage: string }
```

## Strict Mode Preferences

- Always use strict mode
- Prefer `strictNullChecks` - use `?.` and `??` operators
- Avoid `!` non-null assertions unless absolutely certain
